          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Kingston Jamaica</placeName>
                                        <add>?</add>
                                        <date>11<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 5613<lb/> May 18<hi
                                                  rend="sup">th</hi></date>.</p>
                              <p>Dear and Respected Friend</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">When your last favor came<lb/> to hand I had
                                        almost been numbered with<lb/>
                                        <sic>with</sic> the dead, but it was Divine will to<lb/>
                                        spare me a little longer on earth where<lb/> I suppose my
                                        mission had not yet been ful<lb/>filled; and truly grateful
                                        am I for this<lb/> consideration (if I may so term it) as it
                                        enables<lb/> me to feel more sensibly my mortality<lb/>
                                        which till then, almost with shame I confess<lb/> it,
                                        thought with a full sense of the power<lb/> and greatness of
                                        an Adored Creator, I had not<lb/> felt, the chill hand of
                                        sickness, never lost<lb/> a nights rest by my own corporeal
                                        com-<lb/>plaining and therefore the blessing of a<lb/> good
                                        constitution and undisturbed health<lb/> caused a
                                        fearlessness, of which I felt too se-<lb/>cure; so my friend
                                                  <add>?</add> in this little evil<lb/> I feel the
                                        good, I am now thank Heaven<lb/> quite restored,
                                                  <del>an</del> from an attack of yellow<lb/> fever,
                                        of which I had lost all fear; a<lb/> few years in this
                                        climate tend so to lessen the<lb/> the vigor both of mind
                                        and body that<lb/> I long to embrace dame winter again.</p>
                              <p>The loss of a fond endearing Mother whose very<lb/> existence was a
                                        pride to my heart, whose tender<lb/> care almost reduced me
                                        to a state of childhood</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>again, in her care I was for five years safe<lb/> from care, and
                                        climate, at her demise my<lb/> heart so faint and weary of
                                        life without her<lb/> yielding to weather and changes, I
                                        became<lb/> for a season quite an object of anxiety<lb/> to
                                        my friends, but again and again I thank<lb/> Heaven that am
                                        quite restored to former<lb/> activity and begin to mingle
                                        with kind friends<lb/> to dispel the gloom I feared too
                                        ungracious<lb/> in the sight of Heaven, to whose will I
                                        honor<lb/> with humble submission praying that in this<lb/>
                                        great affliction I have atoned for many
                                        trans-<lb/>gressions.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I have <sic>receivd</sic> your last few
                                        numbers<lb/> of Occident regularly, but my volumes are<lb/>
                                        quite incomplete requiring several numbers<lb/> which if I
                                        cannot obtain from <persName>Mr Lawston</persName>,<lb/> I
                                        shall <del>be much obliged to you</del> make known<lb/> to
                                        you (God willing) in my next. I have had<lb/> several
                                        applications for my work and<lb/> am entirely out of
                                                  <del>them</del> a single copy.<lb/> on order from
                                                  <placeName>England</placeName> and by a most<lb/>
                                        favorable opportunity had to pass without<lb/> the supply
                                        you will therefore greatly oblige<lb/> me by sending
                                        immediately 4 dozens and<lb/> let me know how many copies
                                        are on<lb/> hand as I think I shall be compelled to<lb/>
                                        furnish a <add>?</add> 3d edition and much desire to<lb/>
                                        get off the 2d entirely. I observed your<lb/>
                                        <add>?</add> yet spirited reply to <persName>Mr
                                                  Jacobs</persName>; your</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>Philosophic and chaste mind could never have<lb/> exchanged
                                                  <add>?</add> equally, course and <add>?</add><lb/>
                                        with his; you have therefore though with<lb/> the touch of a
                                        gentleman and <sic>schollar</sic> han-<lb/>dled him with
                                        heavy hand than he had ex-<lb/>pected; I did not fail to
                                        prove this to your<lb/> general reading as opportunity
                                        occurred.<lb/> I feel that I have not been in proper
                                        cor-<lb/>respondence with my good and valued friend<lb/> of
                                                  <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>. I
                                        nevertheless <del>for</del> yet re-<lb/>tain all the warmth,
                                        and attachment, I<lb/> ever did neither time nor climate
                                        can<lb/> ever chill the ardent affection for my<lb/> beloved
                                        friends, to all of whom as you my<lb/>
                                        <add>?</add> will tell the same as from me<lb/> To my friend
                                                  <persName>Mr Abm Hart</persName> I shall write
                                        at<lb/> the closing of this. My loving friend,
                                                  <persName>Miss Gratz</persName><lb/> I find is yet
                                        exercising all her usual bene-<lb/>volence, and still active
                                        in promoting and<lb/> circulating that invaluable treasure;
                                        Education<lb/> I yet hope for the day when I shall
                                        greet<lb/> you all again for as I said in a former
                                        letter<lb/> to you, though, my Brother his wife, and<lb/>
                                        family endeavor to make me as comfort-<lb/>able as possible,
                                        being in case and indeed <add>?</add> as<lb/> yet, what is
                                        life without <add>?</add>fulness; this<lb/> is not the
                                        country for the single <add>?</add><lb/> happy and good for
                                        Mothers <add>?</add> families<lb/> who have a high duty to
                                        perform in the<lb/> domestic tracing of their homestead
                                        &amp;c &amp;c but<lb/> for a mind like mine ever active in
                                        public good</p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p>to be <add>?</add> up, (however delightful the<lb/> dwelling may
                                        be) and only meeting a congregation<lb/> on the
                                        <add>?</add>, or be absent from home<lb/> half the year, in
                                        order to attend divine worth of<lb/> in <add>?</add> and
                                        endurance; I therefore am not<lb/> happy with all their
                                        efforts to make me so.<lb/> I have noticed per Occident all
                                        the doings<add>?</add> in<lb/> our various congregations and
                                        read of their<lb/> zeal with much soul stirring
                                        gratification, ho-<lb/>ping once more to be in the field of
                                        usefulness<lb/> among them. Love to <persName>Mrs
                                                  C</persName> tell her I expect<lb/> to find her a
                                        happy grandma. Be kind enough<lb/> to let me know in your
                                        next if you have<lb/> met with a <persName>Mr Joseph
                                                  Aarons</persName>, now Physician<lb/> in
                                                  <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>, studied <hi
                                                  rend="underline">Theology</hi> for a short<lb/>
                                        time with <persName>Dr Raphael</persName> at <hi
                                                  rend="underline">least</hi> so he says in his<lb/>
                                        letters, was professor at Girard College; and as I<lb/>
                                        believe <hi rend="underline">Professing</hi> many things,
                                        and performing nothing<lb/> however this to yourself; only
                                        let me know if you<lb/> have filled my sheet and I have
                                        finished up<lb/> sentiments, so farewell my friend with
                                        best<lb/> wishes for your happiness I remain</p>
                              <p rend="indent(8)">Yours sincerely</p>
                              <p rend="indent(8)">
                                        <persName role="author">Simha</persName>
                              </p>
                              <p>Grandpa's kind regard<lb/> to you, his eyes not<lb/> yet operated
                                        on. <persName>Rachel's</persName><lb/> kind regards also</p>
                    </body>
